07:31.994 --> 07:33.454
"Who is Roger Stone?"

07:39.042 --> 07:42.172
<i>A mock election was planned
in my elementary school.</i>

07:42.254 --> 07:46.054
And I was for John F. Kennedy
because my parents were Catholic,

07:46.133 --> 07:47.933
and I thought, although
they were Republicans,

07:48.010 --> 07:50.350
they had a certain
sympathy for Kennedy.

07:50.428 --> 07:54.348
<i>But also because Kennedy's hair was
so much better than Nixon's hair.</i>

07:54.432 --> 07:56.852
<i>And, therefore, I
went to the cafeteria</i>

07:56.934 --> 07:59.694
<i>and as each kid would go
through the cafeteria line with their tray,</i>

07:59.771 --> 08:02.481
I would tell them, "You
know, Nixon has proposed

08:02.565 --> 08:04.645
having school on Saturdays."

08:05.568 --> 08:07.898
Well, then the mock
election was held,

08:07.988 --> 08:10.118
and to the surprise of
the local newspaper,

08:10.198 --> 08:13.198
<i>Democrat John Kennedy
swept this mock election.</i>

08:13.285 --> 08:17.655
For the first time ever, I understood
the value of disinformation.

08:17.747 --> 08:19.867
Of course, I've never
practiced it since then.

08:23.461 --> 08:24.671
We Republicans seek

08:24.754 --> 08:28.054
a government that attends to
its inherent responsibilities,

08:28.633 --> 08:32.303
encouraging a free and
a competitive economy,

08:32.970 --> 08:35.600
and enforcing law and order.

08:38.684 --> 08:42.015
<i>My first Republican
National Convention was 1964.</i>

08:42.105 --> 08:43.684
<i>I was 12 years old.</i>

08:43.773 --> 08:47.153
<i>The woman who lived next door to
me, she gave me a copy of a book,</i>

08:47.235 --> 08:49.605
The Conscience of a Conservative
<i>by Barry Goldwater.</i>

08:49.696 --> 08:52.486
<i>And I devoured this book
in, you know, a day.</i>

08:52.574 --> 08:55.454
It was at that moment that I
knew what I wanted to do.

08:55.535 --> 08:59.245
I no longer wanted to be an actor.
I now wanted to be in politics.

08:59.331 --> 09:01.921
<i>Little did I know how
similar they are.</i>

09:01.999 --> 09:04.959
I became a zealot. I had a
Goldwater sticker on my bicycle.

09:05.045 --> 09:06.585
I wore Goldwater buttons.

09:06.671 --> 09:09.221
I wore a Goldwater button two
weeks after the election was over.

09:09.299 --> 09:10.969
That's how defiant I was.

09:12.510 --> 09:14.050
<i>I met Roger in college.</i>

09:14.137 --> 09:17.887
<i>He was really a total prodigy,
in terms of his political ability.</i>

09:17.974 --> 09:23.404
He was talking grown men back
home into running for office, electing them.

09:23.480 --> 09:25.610
And then we would
sit in our dorm room

09:25.690 --> 09:28.030
and they would call
Roger for political advice

09:28.110 --> 09:30.320
as to how they should
vote on key issues.

09:30.903 --> 09:33.413
<i>His mother once said,
"You're not a Catholic.</i>

09:33.490 --> 09:37.490
Your religion is the Republican Party
and your god is Richard Nixon."

09:38.870 --> 09:41.660
<i>Bart Porter asked him,
you know, if he'd be interested</i>

09:41.748 --> 09:43.538
in coming to the Nixon campaign,

09:43.625 --> 09:47.625
so Roger took time off of
school to go join the campaign.

09:47.712 --> 09:51.342
<i>This is central headquarters
for the Re-Elect Nixon Campaign.</i>

09:51.424 --> 09:52.514
<i>The White House.</i>

09:52.592 --> 09:54.142
<i>But for the sake of appearances,</i>

09:54.219 --> 09:59.179
<i>the Re-Elect Nixon headquarters, in name,
is one block up Pennsylvania Avenue.</i>

09:59.266 --> 10:00.976
<i>The Committee to
Re-Elect the President</i>

10:01.058 --> 10:04.228
<i>was unlike any campaign
that I'd been in.</i>

10:04.312 --> 10:06.652
<i>It didn't look like your typical
political headquarters.</i>

10:06.731 --> 10:09.531
It had a very hushed,
corporate quality to it.

10:11.819 --> 10:13.949
<i>Porter called me into
his office and said,</i>

10:14.030 --> 10:15.910
<i>"We want you to go
to New Hampshire,</i>

10:15.990 --> 10:18.620
<i>and we want you to give this
contribution to Pete McCloskey,</i>

10:18.701 --> 10:20.701
<i>who's running for the
Republican nomination,</i>

10:20.787 --> 10:22.867
<i>challenging Nixon from the left,</i>

10:22.955 --> 10:25.745
in the name of the Young
Socialist Alliance."

10:25.833 --> 10:27.383
I got an enormous mason jar,

10:27.460 --> 10:30.630
filled it with pennies and
nickels and dimes and quarters.

10:30.713 --> 10:33.223
<i>I brought it to the
McCloskey headquarters.</i>

10:33.300 --> 10:34.880
I said, "Hi, I'm from the
Young Socialist Alliance.

10:34.967 --> 10:37.757
I wanna donate this,
and I need a receipt."

10:37.845 --> 10:39.755
They were so dumb,
they gave me one.

10:39.847 --> 10:43.187
The idea was to give the receipt
to the <i>Manchester Union Leader,</i>

10:43.268 --> 10:47.398
the largest newspaper in New Hampshire,
as a way of discrediting McCloskey.

10:47.480 --> 10:53.700
A perfect example of a dirty trick
that had no purpose and no effect,

10:53.778 --> 10:55.658
but the Nixon people
thought it was great.

10:55.738 --> 10:57.658
I never heard another
word about it...

10:57.740 --> 11:01.410
until an investigator from the Senate
Watergate Committee knocked on my door.

11:01.494 --> 11:03.794
<i>We have a mystery
story out of Washington.</i>

11:03.871 --> 11:05.581
<i>Five people have been
arrested and charged</i>

11:05.665 --> 11:08.285
<i>with breaking into the headquarters
of the Democratic National Committee</i>

11:08.376 --> 11:09.376
<i>in the middle of the night.</i>

11:09.461 --> 11:11.301
<i>The Democratic
National Committee is located</i>

11:11.379 --> 11:13.089
<i>in the Watergate
office building.</i>

11:13.172 --> 11:15.012
I welcome this kind
of examination,

11:15.091 --> 11:18.931
because people have got to know whether
or not their president is a crook.

11:19.011 --> 11:20.391
Well, I'm not a crook.

11:20.472 --> 11:22.772
I've earned everything I've got.

11:22.849 --> 11:25.849
I was the youngest person to go
to the Watergate grand jury.

11:27.354 --> 11:29.984
<i>During the Senate Watergate
Committee hearings,</i>

11:30.064 --> 11:31.824
this enormous chart was put up,

11:31.899 --> 11:37.279
<i>in which everyone who received money from
this secret fund was put on the wall.</i>

11:37.364 --> 11:41.664
And it said, "Gordon
Liddy, McCord, Segretti."

11:41.743 --> 11:43.833
<i>And then way down at the
bottom, it said "Stone."</i>

11:43.911 --> 11:49.171
I paid $100 to Mr. Roger
Stone on one occasion.

11:49.251 --> 11:53.091
My parents called me on the phone.
They were mortified.

11:53.170 --> 11:55.010
I thought it was pretty cool.

11:55.089 --> 11:57.629
To leave office before
my term is completed

11:57.717 --> 12:00.387
is abhorrent to every
instinct in my body.

12:00.470 --> 12:06.310
<i>But as president, I must put the
interests of America first.</i>

12:06.392 --> 12:11.942
Therefore, I shall resign the
presidency effective at noon tomorrow.

12:13.107 --> 12:15.687
<i>I was a Watergate
figure at 19 years old.</i>

12:16.278 --> 12:19.198
<i>I mean, at the time, I
was scared shitless.</i>

12:19.281 --> 12:20.821
<i>It was very hard to find work.</i>

12:20.907 --> 12:23.827
<i>We used to have these buttons
that said "hire a Watergate vet."</i>

12:33.044 --> 12:36.464
<i>So this is the Batcave. This is
"the Factory," as we call it.</i>

12:37.214 --> 12:40.394
<i>This is where I tape my
Saturday radio shows.</i>

12:40.468 --> 12:42.388
It is also the repository

12:42.470 --> 12:47.020
of probably the world's largest
collection of Nixon memorabilia.

12:47.099 --> 12:50.309
The 1962 campaign for governor.

12:50.395 --> 12:52.355
Uh, a rally that I
actually attended.

12:52.438 --> 12:54.978
A head shot poster of the day.

12:55.483 --> 12:59.573
This is protesting Nixon's
historic trip to China.

12:59.654 --> 13:04.374
Here you have the first and
second generation Nixon bongs.

13:04.451 --> 13:07.661
This is among my most
prized possessions.

13:07.745 --> 13:10.705
<i>Roger Stone does occasional
political chores for Nixon.</i>

13:10.790 --> 13:15.590
<i>One such chore, to organize dinners of
journalists at Nixon's New Jersey home.</i>

13:16.338 --> 13:20.128
<i>I was the assigned liaison
between the Reagan campaign</i>

13:20.216 --> 13:23.886
and former President Nixon,
transmitting memos back and forth.

13:23.970 --> 13:27.600
<i>It was not until his post-presidency
that we became close friends.</i>

13:27.682 --> 13:29.352
<i>He had been through
a lot, obviously,</i>

13:29.434 --> 13:31.694
<i>but I think he was just
as resilient as ever.</i>

13:31.769 --> 13:34.109
His greatest single
quality is resilience.

13:34.188 --> 13:37.188
<i>And that's the purpose
of my tattoo.</i>

13:37.274 --> 13:39.194
<i>It's not an ideological
statement.</i>

13:39.276 --> 13:42.606
<i>It's a reminder that in life,
when you get knocked down,</i>

13:42.697 --> 13:46.447
you have to get up off the canvas and
keep pushing, get back in the game.

13:46.534 --> 13:48.294
That's the story of Nixon.

13:48.370 --> 13:53.790
A man is not finished when he is defeated.
He's only finished when he quits.

13:54.417 --> 13:58.207
<i>The Nixon tattoo is really
all you need to know about Roger.</i>

13:58.713 --> 14:01.973
Because he thinks Nixon's
approach to politics,

14:02.049 --> 14:05.759
the toughness, the
win-at-all-costs mentality,

14:05.845 --> 14:07.965
that's what Roger reflects.

14:08.055 --> 14:11.015
Delegates to the Young Republicans
Convention in Memphis

14:11.100 --> 14:14.900
have chosen as their chairman a
conservative with a Watergate past.

14:14.979 --> 14:16.979
<i>Watergate
dominated this convention</i>

14:17.064 --> 14:19.824
<i>because the Republican
Party's important youth arm</i>

14:19.901 --> 14:24.451
<i>was about to be taken over by Roger
Stone, a 25-year-old political operative</i>

14:24.531 --> 14:28.951
<i>who was deeply involved in the 1972
Nixon "dirty tricks" campaign.</i>

14:29.035 --> 14:32.035
<i>They embellished what
was a 20-year-old kid's role</i>

14:32.121 --> 14:34.581
<i>into being the
mastermind of Watergate.</i>

14:34.666 --> 14:38.706
Roger saw the opportunity
to build a reputation

14:38.795 --> 14:41.585
off of being viewed as that
politically significant.

14:41.673 --> 14:43.433
<i>Opponents
of Stone contend</i>

14:43.508 --> 14:46.388
<i>that his election is part of a
move by conservative activists</i>

14:46.469 --> 14:48.719
<i>to take over the
Republican Party.</i>

14:48.805 --> 14:50.345
<i>When
we elected Roger,</i>

14:50.431 --> 14:53.641
<i>we moved the Republican Party in
a more ideological direction.</i>

14:54.143 --> 14:58.023
Up until that point, it was straddling
the old Republican establishment

14:58.105 --> 15:01.895
<i>and the new conservative movement that
was started in Barry Goldwater days.</i>

15:01.984 --> 15:03.324
We built on that,

15:03.403 --> 15:06.783
and I think when Roger was elected
chairman of the Young Republicans,

15:06.864 --> 15:10.124
<i>you know, that was the piece
that finalized everything.</i>

15:10.201 --> 15:12.241
For many years, the
Republican Party

15:12.328 --> 15:17.038
<i>was associated with this sort of
good guy, Eisenhower earnestness.</i>

15:17.542 --> 15:19.132
What happened with the new right

15:19.210 --> 15:21.960
was there was a new generation
of people who said,

15:22.046 --> 15:25.546
"You know what? We're gonna fight
dirty and we're gonna win."

